The unemployment rate jumped from a 50-year low of 3.5% to 4.4%, highest since August 2017, the Labor Department said Friday.
U.S. stocks turned lower Friday in another volatile trading session after the government reported the big job losses.
By comparison, it took about two years for the economy to lose nearly nine million jobs during the Great Recession.
